SIDA, non-transmissible diseases in eight key points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as cardiovascular diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, sedentary lifestyle, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet, despite widespread knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
This was the context in which alliances for non-communicable diseases came together from December 9 to 11 at the second Global Forum on Non-Communicable Diseases in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions aimed at regulating MTNs, they should draw inspiration from the movement against AIDS.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress made.
While the battle is not yet over, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against MTNs could push back this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the MTN community as being in need of an "electroshock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who has the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from the activists fighting HIV/AIDS.
While global attention focuses on preventing NMTs, those who seek to control avoidable diseases should draw inspiration from the ABCs of HIV/AIDS organizations.
The first letter that the NMT community must take into account is "A", as in activism.
Anyone over 40 remembers surely the images of HIV/AIDS activists participating in "die-ins" at scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, activists fighting HIV/AIDS took to the streets, even shutting down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
At a global level, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Then, the NCD community must adopt a more bold approach to budgets - the "B" of the AIDS movement strategy.
Civil society and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energy, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires funding.
The AIDS movement was clear about this from the outset and pressed for resources to support its awareness and empowerment activities effectively.
"C" represents coalitions: AIDS-fighting movements did not take long to realize that progress comes only with multiple supports.
Militants established connections between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Campaign coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders to public authorities, combining their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS-fighting movement has also understood that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential for spreading its support.
Thus, "D," the key determinant of success, consisted of 'highlighting the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying leaders in education to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make smart decisions about when and with whom to negotiate safe sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a key role in the AIDS crisis.
The MNT are not less isolated in their causality and also face a multi-sector approach to prevention.
The engagement - "E" - has been what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which defended the catchphrase "Nothing about us without us," AIDS advocates demanded representation for organizations in place to treat the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Governing Board for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply integrated into the AIDS advocacy movement that it would almost be unthinkable for an AIDS-related meeting to take place without civil society representation.
AIDS prevention movements must also develop compelling stories and "F" - framing the question - is essential for the AIDS community to secure political leadership support.
Access to AIDS treatments has been presented in particular as an issue of economic justice.
Formulating the story this way has led to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the point where more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are now on treatment.
A formulation equally important for AIDS, a very pertinent question for the LNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to put more emphasis on people's life choices rather than attributing state responsibility for healthcare delivery and the elimination of legal discrimination.
In the AIDS debate, gender - the "G" of our movement - was a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a "gay disease," and gender identity was rooted in the DNA of the AIDS activism movement from the start.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to examine how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to see this.
The gender, therefore, must become a focal point for MNT prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" - human rights - are the foundation of the AIDS response.
Campaigns have been launched against workplace discrimination, in schools, and in medical centers.
Litigation has ensured equality under the law.
The AIDS resistance movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with laws repressively targeting people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit unhealthy food advertising to children.
We could continue down the alphabet listing the lessons learned from the fight against AIDS, but we believe it is appropriate to close on "H", given that human rights provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization, increase people's risk to HIV.
This is also true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS-fighting movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet in premature death from avoidable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The MNT and HIV communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The views expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
